umanist and political literature of the period, Jordan shows that Shakespeare's abusive rulers suffer as much as they impose on their subjects. Shakespeare's Monarchies recognizes the romances as politically inflected texts and confirms Shakespeare's involvement in the public discourse of the period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 0aKings and rulers in literature. 0aMonarchy in literature. 0aPolitical plays, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitics and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aTragicomedyxHistory and criticism. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501744433423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501744433.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG